                <section>
                    <title> Internet</title>
                    <p>Skills Addressed in this Lesson:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p> Access the Internet from the Main Menu.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Type in and go to a specific web page.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Read a web page.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Move from link to link and open links when desired.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Access and use input controls.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Utilize the favorites list.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Use the history list.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Use computer Braille as necessary.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <subsection>
                        <title>Tasks</title>
                        <p>Complete the tasks listed below with your student.  This lesson assumes that you have access to the Internet.</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> Assist your student in removing the compact flash card from the back of the BrailleNote if there is one inserted.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Help your student to insert the network card into the appropriate slot in the BrailleNote.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> From the Main Menu of the BrailleNote, access the internet by keying in the letter i. At this point the url (address) of a web page will be displayed.  By default, the web address of PulseData is displayed.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> The following tasks can be accomplished from the url address.  To learn these options listed for yourself, push space with h for help.</p>
                            </li>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p> One option is to type in a url or a favorite name and press enter.  You will be taken to the web site that you typed in.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> For a local file, type backspace, then the file name.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To access the favorite list and saved html files, press space.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Space with dots5 6 will access the browser history list.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Use computer Braille to type the name of a web address.  This means you may not use Braille contractions and you must use dots4 6 for a dot(period).</p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> After you have pressed i from Main Menu to go to the internet, press enter to go to the web address displayed.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> You may need to press enter to access your internet service or space to it and press enter.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Practice reading the web page you opened.  Use the following commands:</p>
                            </li>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Press space with g to go forward reading.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Go to the top of the page when necessary with space and dots1 2 3.  Space with dots4 5 6 will go to the bottom of the page.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To find a text string, press space with f.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To move back a character and forward by character, use space with dot3 or space with dot6. Space with dots3 and 6 will read the current character.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To hear the current word, press space with dots2 5.  Space with dot2 or space with dot5 will move back or forward by word.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To read back and forward by sentence, use space with dot4 or space with dot1.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Space with dots2 3 will move back by paragraph.  Space with dots5 6 will move forward by paragraph.  Space with dots2 3 5 6 will read the current paragraph.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Space with m will determine the current reading mode.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Space with m repeated will change the current reading mode.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Enter with dots5 6 will move to the next text section.  Enter with dots2 3 will move to the previous text section.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Space with w will announce the key name.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To query the current cursor position, use space with dots1 5 6.</p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> Practice with the Thumb-Key Commands</p>
                            </li>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p> The advance thumb-key will advance the display by a width.  Use the back thumb-key to move the display back by a width of the Braille display.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Use space with dots1 2 4 5 6 to start the Braille display moving automatically.  Use the previous or next thumb-keys to control the speed.  To stop, press previous and next together.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Previous with back will move the display back a word.  Previous with advance will move the display on a word.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> The previous thumb-key with space will change speech to on or off.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> The next thumb-key with space will change the Braille display mode.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Back with advance will route the cursor to the beginning of the Braille display.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To cycle through the four Braille display modes, press previous and next repeatedly.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> The advance thumb-key with the next thumb-key repeatedly will cycle through the text file display options.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> On the Pulse Data page, go to the top of the page by using space with dots1 2 3.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Now type a g for the Google search engine link.  Then press enter and you will go to the Google url.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Conduct a search for a specific topic of interest on the Google page. To get to the text input control, press space with dots4 and 6.  Use computer Braille to key in the name of a topic.  Press space with dots4 and 6 to move to the next input control, which should be the search button.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Press enter to begin the search.  You may also just press enter after you write in the search edit box.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Use space to move forward by link.  Move back by link by pressing backspace.  Explore the results of your search.  Press enter on a link to open the url. Use the web browser and miscellaneous commands listed here. Practice as necessary.</p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> Web Browser and Miscellaneous Commands</p>
                            </li>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Use enter with o to open a new url.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Space with i will display the name of the current web page.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Press enter to click a button.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Enter with f will go forward in a session history list.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Enter with b will go back a page in the session history list.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To refresh the current web page, press enter with the letter r.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To access the favorites menu, press enter with a low f (dots2 3 5).</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Enter with m will go to the internet options menu.  From the internet options menu, you may:</p>
                                </li>
                                <ol>
                                    <li>
                                        <p> open an html file</p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p> set the current page as the home page</p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p> go to your home page</p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p> manage internet files</p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p> go to the display settings</p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p> print the current web page</p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p> check the error status</p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p> Enter with lower h (dots2 3 6 will go to the history list).</p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p> Space with dots1 3 will go to the previous input control.  Space with dots4 and 6 will go to the next input control.  Space with dots1 3 4 6 will read the current input control.</p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p> Space with b will take you to the block commands menu.</p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p> To access the spelling checker, use space with dots1 6.</p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p> Space with s will save a file.</p>
                                    </li>
                                </ol>
                            </ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> Remember, at any time you can press the initial letter of a link to go directly to it.  Practice using only the basic commands at first.</p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </subsection>
                    <subsection>
                        <title>Quiz</title>
                        <p>Give a short answer to each question.</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> What will space with dots4 and 6 do?</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Space with what will display the name of the current web page?</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> How can you start the Braille display moving automatically?</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> What will using the previous thumb-key with the space turn on and off?</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> When using the Internet, enter with dots2 3 5 will do what?</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> When on a web page, what can you use to move from link to link?</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> What will enter with m bring up?</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> When using computer Braille, which Braille dotsmake a period?</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> When using the Internet, what will space with dots4 5 6 do?</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> What will take you to the history list?</p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </subsection>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <title> Book Reader</title>
                    <p>Skills Addressed in this Lesson:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p> Enter the book reader.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Select a book to read.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Use the appropriate commands required in reading a book.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Explore the Bookshare site to locate books.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Download books to the BrailleNote.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Unpack books as necessary.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <subsection>
                        <title>Tasks</title>
                        <p>This lesson assumes you are able to connect the BrailleNote to the Internet and that you have an account with Bookshare.</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> First we need to go to the Bookshare site to download and unpack books. With the BrailleNote connected to the Internet, press an i from the Main Menu of the BrailleNote.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> At the address prompt, write the Bookshare web address and press enter.  Connect to a service by pressing enter at the cue.  You should be taken to the Bookshare web site.  Press space with dots4 6 to go to the first edit box where your e-mail address can be entered.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> As a reminder, if you get a security alert, press enter on the yes button.  This lesson may vary.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> At the e-mail text edit box, write in the e-mail address of your account.  Then use space with 4 6 again to go to the password edit box.  Write the password of your account.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> To get to the submit button, press space with 4 and 6 again.  Press enter.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Press h to go to the home page link.  Press enter.  At this point, help your student explore the various categories of books.  Press a b to get to the "browse category" link and press enter.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Press c to get to the "categories$"$  link. At this point, press an "a" to get to the first category "animals." Then use space or backspace to explore the various categories.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Categories include areas such as animals, biographies and memoirs, children's books, entertainment, horror, mystery and thrillers, poetry, sports, and teen.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Here are the steps I followed in getting a book from the teen category.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Follow a similar pattern to help your student find and download books of interest. This lesson may vary as updates to the site are made.</p>
                            </li>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Press space or a t to locate the "teen" category.  Press enter to go to the teen page.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Space to the "skip to main content" link. Press enter. You will be placed in a table of book titles, authors, and book formats.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> If you find a book you want to download, enter on brf or daisy to begin downloading the book.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To learn more about a book before downloading it, press enter on the book title.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> "Download file into which folder?" will be the cue.  I have a folder called Bookshare, so I download all of my books in one folder.  Press enter at the appropriate folder.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> At the "download file name?" prompt, press enter if the name is suitable for you.  You will be given a cue when the file is finished downloading.  Use the command to go back to the previous web page you were at. Get three or four books at this time if you wish.</p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> Now your student or you need to unpack the books.  To do this, go to the book reader from the Main Menu by pressing a b.  To get to the book reader from anywhere, press a b with enter and backspace.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> "Read book in which folder?" will be the cue.  Press enter on the bookshare folder, or whatever folder you have saved the book you want to unpack in. You may need to press space with x to get a list of all file types in order to find the book in the list.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Space to the title of the book you want to unpack.  Press enter. "Folder for unpacked bookshare book?" will be the next cue.  Press enter on the appropriate folder.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> "Password" is the next cue.  Write your Bookshare password using computer Braille and press enter.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> At the prompt, "delete the original packed bookshare book?" press a y for yes.  You will be told when the book is unpacked by the BrailleNote giving the title of the unpacked book.  Press enter at "review the options" to go into the unpacked book.  If you are asked if you want to delete the packed book, press y for yes if you want to delete it.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> To delete a book from folder, press backspace with dots1 4 when pointed to the book you want to delete.  At the prompt to double check for erasing the book, press a y for yes to confirm that you want to delete the book.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Return to the Main Menu and turn the BrailleNote off.</p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                        <p>You will need keysoft version 7.5, build 31 (or higher) to use bookshare.</p>
                    </subsection>
                    <subsection>
                        <title>Quiz</title>
                        <p>True or False</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> You do not need an account with Bookshare to download books from the Bookshare site.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Press a space with b to enter the BrailleNote book reader from anywhere.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> To move to the next input control on a web page, use space with dots1 and 3.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Fishing is one of the Bookshare categories.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Bookshare only has newspapers and magazines to download.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> You do not need build 31 or higher to use bookshare.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> For reading Braille books on the BrailleNote, it is best to use the wav format.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> It is good to delete the packed copy of a book after you have unpacked it to save space on the BrailleNote.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Once you have downloaded a book onto the BrailleNote, you cannot erase it.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> The book reader should be used for reading books.</p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </subsection>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <title> Scientific Calculator</title>
                    <p>Skills Addressed in this Lesson:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p> Enter the BrailleNote scientific calculator from the Main Menu.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Enter the scientific calculator by using the shortcut key.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Complete division, multiplication, addition, and subtraction problems by using the calculator.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Use decimal points if they are needed.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Get help from within the scientific calculator.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Insert a calculation into a word document.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Quickly switch between the scientific calculator and a keyword document.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Exit the calculator.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <subsection>
                        <title>Tasks</title>
                        <p>Adjust this lesson according to the grade and ability level of your student.</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> From the Main Menu, instruct your student to space until scientific calculator is spoken or displayed.  Press enter to open the calculator.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> On the Braille display, your student will feel the number 0.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Use e with space to return to the Main Menu.  A full cell with space will also get you back to the Main Menu.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Ask your student to explain another way in which the scientific calculator can be opened from the Main Menu.  Yes, press the letter s for scientific calculator to open the application.  When the calculator is open, do not exit to the Main Menu this time.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Press backspace with enter with w to open the keyword application.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Encourage your student to create a document in a folder called Math.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Create a folder if necessary by writing the word math at the "folder to open" cue.  When asked if you want to create the folder, press y for yes.  Make a new file within the folder called "practice 1" for use during this lesson.  Again, just write the file name when prompted to do so.  Answer y for yes when asked if you want to create the file.  Give your student help as needed.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> At the top of the blank document, your student may write a heading.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> The first line may contain the student's name.  Follow this with a new line by pressing the enter key.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Your student may write the date on the second line.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> The third line of the document can contain the assignment name "Math Practice." Notice that both words of the assignment name are capitalized.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Many teachers require students to include a heading on assignments and tests.  Students who are blind or visually impaired should not be exempt from requirements that their nondisabled peers must abide by.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Follow the heading with two new lines.  Your student should write 1 followed by a period and a space to get ready for the first math problem.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> The shortcut for opening the calculator is enter with backspace with</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> s. Your student should do this now.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> In the calculator, you do not need to use the numeric indicator "the number sign." You or your student may use upper or lower case numbers.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Nemeth Code users may want to practice dropping their numbers while using the scientific calculator to remain in the habit of using Braille math.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Help your student complete a simple addition problem.  The addition sign is dots3 4 6.  To obtain a result, press the enter key.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Now your student may clear the calculator by pushing backspace with dots1 4.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Try a subtraction problem.  The subtraction sign is dots3 6.  Use a variety of numbers so that your student can practice inputting numbers into the scientific calculator.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> After clearing the result, try some multiplication problems.  The multiplication sign is dots1 6.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> The division sign is dots3 4.  If you need a decimal point, use dots4 6.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> At any time you may get extensive help from within the scientific calculator.  Press space with h.  Your student should try this now.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> In the calculator help menu, your student can space to the areas of General Commands, Basic Functions, Fractions, Memory Commands, Scientific Functions, and Statistics.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Enter on any item to read more about it.  Your student should explore commands and information in the scientific calculator help menu to learn specific commands and tasks based on his or her grade or ability level. The BrailleNote gives terrific help from anywhere.  You and your student can learn an awesome amount of information by taking advantage of this feature from anywhere on the BrailleNote.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Use e with space to go back by level until you get back to the scientific calculator.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> At the scientific calculator entry point, complete an addition problem, then get the result.  Do not clear the answer this time.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Press enter with backspace with w to return to the document you created earlier in this lesson.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Ensure that your cursor is placed after number 1.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Insert your calculator result into your document.  Press enter with i.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Then press c for calculation.</p>
                            </li>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To insert the result, press r.  Press c to insert the whole calculation.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Did this work? Allow your student time to check.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Practice this skill.  Press enter with backspace with s to go back to the scientific calculator.  Clear your result.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Complete a new math problem.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Press enter with backspace with w to return to your document.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Use enter with i to insert the result.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Practice these skills until your student is able to demonstrate independence in using the scientific calculator for basic operations.  Also ensure that your student is able to independently insert calculations into keyword documents.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Requiring your student to exhibit the skill of switching quickly from a keyword document to the scientific calculator and back to a keyword document will ensure mastery of skills outlined in this lesson.</p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </ol>
                    </subsection>
                    <subsection>
                        <title>Quiz</title>
                        <p>Write or say the best answer to each question.</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> What is the shortcut to get to the scientific calculator from within a keyword document?</p>
                            </li>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p> enter with s</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> enter with backspace with c</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> enter with backspace with s</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> enter with c</p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> Which dotsmake the minus sign?</p>
                            </li>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p> dots3 4 6</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> dots4 6</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> dots1 6</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> dots3 6</p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            <li>
