                <section>
                    <title> Book Reader</title>
                    <p>Skills Addressed in this Lesson:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p> Open the book reader.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Open a book.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Locate the beginning of a book.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Open a second book using the shortcut command.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Navigate through a book.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Use the thumb-keys within a book.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <subsection>
                        <title>Tasks</title>
                        <p>This lesson assumes you have downloaded at least two books from a web site such as Web Braille or Bookshare. Give assistance as necessary.</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> From Main Menu, press b for book reader.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> The book reader will open.  You will be asked to open a folder, then to open a book.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> You may have to unpack a book if you have used Bookshare. You will need to know your Bookshare user name and password.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> From the top of the book, you may want to locate the beginning of the book content without reading all of the initial copyright information.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> You will need to use the find command.  Press space with f.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Press f to search forward.  The letter b will search "back" if you needed to find something behind the cursor.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Key in "isbn" for the isbn number of the book.  Press enter.  This will get you closer to the beginning of the book content.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> You could also key in the words "begin content" to get closer to the beginning of the book.  Use other words of your choice to find the beginning content of the book.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> From within the book, you can always use space with h.  When pressing space with h, you can space to the help topics of:</p>
                            </li>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Review commands</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Braille thumb-key commands</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Miscellaneous commands</p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> If you are reading with speech, you can press space with g to go forward reading.  Press enter with backspace to stop reading.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Space with f will help you search for a string of text in the book. Use this command if you loose your place and need to locate it again.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Use space with n to find the next occurrence of the last searched-for text string.  If you searched for the word "chapter" and did not find the correct chapter, you could use space with n to search for the word "chapter" again.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Allow your student time to practice these commands.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Other navigation commands that are similar to the navigation commands in a keyword document can also be used in the book reader.  Practice the below commands as necessary.</p>
                            </li>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Space with 1 2 3 will go to the top of the document.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Go to the end of the document with space and dots4 5 6.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Move back by character with space and dot3. Read the current character with space and dots3 6.  Read the next character with space and dot6.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Read back by word with space and dot2. Read the current word with space and dots2 5.  Read the next word with space and dot5.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Space with dot1 or space with dot4 will read back and forward by sentence.  Space with dots1 4 will read the current sentence.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To read back and forward by paragraph, use space with dots2 3 or space with dots5 6.  Space with dots2 3 5 6 will read the current paragraph.</p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> To be an efficient Braille reader, use the BrailleNote without speech.  Use the thumb-keys and the Braille display.  Practice the below commands as appropriate.</p>
                            </li>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Use the back thumb-key to move back by one Braille display width.  Use the advance thumb-key to move forward by one Braille display width.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To start the display moving automatically, press space with dots1 2 4 5 6.  Press the previous thumb-key to slow down the speed of automatic reading.  The next thumb-key will increase the rate of automatic reading.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To stop automatic reading, pres the previous and next thumb-keys at the same time.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> For more thumb-key commands, visit the help menu from within a book.</p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> Other commands you and your student can practice within a book are:</p>
                            </li>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To go to the block commands menu, press space with b.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> To move to another book, press space with dots1 2 5 6.</p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> Read a book from within the book reader.  Practice using the commands with your student that will be most useful to your given situation.</p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </subsection>
                    <subsection>
                        <title>Quiz</title>
                        <p>True or False:</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> Space with dots2 3 4 5 6 will start the display moving automatically.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Space with dots3 6 will read the current line.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> The previous thumb-key will slow the rate of automatic reading.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Space with e or space with a full cell will return to the Main Menu.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Space with 1 2 3 will go to the end of a book.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Space with l will help you find the location of a text string.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Space with 4 will move forward by sentence.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> B from the Main Menu will open the book reader.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Space with n will go to the top of the file.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Space with dot3 will move forward by character.</p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </subsection>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <title> Braille Options Menu</title>
                    <p>Skills Addressed in this Lesson:</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p> Go to the Options Menu.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> From within the Options Menu, go to the Braille Options menu.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Alter the Braille option settings as necessary.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> Return to Main Menu.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                    <subsection>
                        <title>Tasks</title>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> From within a keyword document, space with o to enter the Options Menu.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> For practice, we will change the Braille Option settings.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Once in the Options Menu, you may press b to open the Braille Options menu.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> The first option is Braille on or off.  To toggle between yes and no, press space with dots3 4.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Space to the Braille Display Mode.  Automatic, reading, editing, and layout are the available modes.  Press enter to leave the item unchanged. Press the initial letter of each item to change to that mode.  Read more about each item below.</p>
                            </li>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p> In automatic mode, the cursor is on when editing.  When reading, the cursor is off.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> The letter r stands for reading mode.  In this mode, the cursor is not on.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> E is for editing.  The cursor is always on and formatting is displayed.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> In layout mode, the document is displayed as it would be if you embossed it.</p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> By pressing the previous and next thumb-keys together, you can change the Braille display mode.  This is the shortcut key.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> When in the Options Menu, you or your student can space to the next item or press backspace to move to the previous item.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> "Show new lines in reading mode" is next in the Braille Options menu. Press space with dots3 4 to cycle between the available options.  Press space with h to get help.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> "Function of previous and next thumb-keys" is next.  Use s for sentence or line.  For paragraph or section, press p.  To have the previous and next thumb-keys move up and down, press u.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Next you may change the cursor shape.  Use b for both dots7 and 8.  For only dot7, press 7.  Press 8 for only dot8. For an 8 dotcell, press w.  6 is for a six dotcell.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Preferred reading grade is next.  This will determine the grade of Braille used on the display for messages, menus, etc.  Press 1 for grade I Braille, 2 for grade II Braille, and c for computer Braille.  Press enter to leave the option unchanged.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Text document reading grade is next.  Press space with h to get help, then make your choice.  Experiment to see what is best for you.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Preferred English Braille code is next.  Space with h will give you the various options.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Computer Braille table is next.  Press space with dots3 and 4 to step through the available options or use the letter hotkey.  Press s for use computer Braille.  K is for UK Braille.  Read more in the User Guide if you need to use this option.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Continue through the additional areas of the Braille Display Options. Space with h to get help when necessary.  The available options are listed below.</p>
                            </li>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Cursor shape for computer Braille.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Braille display intensity.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Display computer Braille as 6 or 8 dots.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Message display time is next.</p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p> Thumb-key set is next.</p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> Use the Options Menu and experiment to see what is best for you.  Explore the other available areas in the options menu.  They may vary according to where you were on the BrailleNote when you opened the Options Menu.</p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </subsection>
                    <subsection>
                        <title>Quiz</title>
                        <p>Write or say each answer.</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> Space with what letter will take you to the options menu?</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> In what menu can you change the Braille settings?</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> When making a choice, what does dots3 4 do among menu options?</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> In what mode is the cursor on when editing.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> What does space with h do in the Options Menu?</p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </subsection>
